Rust's ownership system ensures memory safety without a garbage collector.

Rules:
1. Each value has one owner
2. Only one owner at a time
3. When owner goes out of scope, value is dropped

```rust
let s1 = String::from("hello");
let s2 = s1;  // s1 MOVED to s2
// println!("{}", s1);  // ERROR: s1 no longer valid

// Clone for explicit deep copy
let s3 = s2.clone();
println!("{} {}", s2, s3);  // Both valid

// Copy types (stack data) are copied, not moved
let x = 5;
let y = x;
println!("{} {}", x, y);  // Both valid — integers implement Copy
```
No null pointers, no dangling pointers, no double-frees. Memory safety at compile time.

Borrowing lets you use a value without taking ownership.

```rust
fn calculate_length(s: &String) -> usize {  // Borrow, don't own
    s.len()
}  // s not dropped — we don't own it

let s = String::from("hello");
let len = calculate_length(&s);  // Pass reference
println!("{} has length {}", s, len);  // s still valid

// Mutable reference
fn change(s: &mut String) {
    s.push_str(", world");
}
let mut s = String::from("hello");
change(&mut s);

// Rules:
// - Many immutable references OR one mutable reference
// - References must always be valid (no dangling)
```
Prevents data races at compile time.

